# setTimeout() is NOT JavaScript

Most developers think this:

```js id="w7w9qb"
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Hello");
}, 2000);
```

starts a timer inside JavaScript.

It doesn’t.

JavaScript engines like V8 have NO built-in timer system.

So what actually happens?

## Behind the scenes

When `setTimeout()` is called:

1. V8 receives the function call
2. It delegates the timer work to the browser/runtime
3. Browser bindings invoke native C++ code
4. The OS handles the actual timer
5. Once completed, the callback is pushed into the task queue
6. The event loop moves it back into JavaScript execution

Simplified internal flow:

```cpp id="p6f34u"
void SetTimeoutCallback(args) {
  StartTimer(delay, [=]() {
    task_queue.push(jsCallback);
  });
}
```

This means the timer itself is running outside the JS engine entirely.

